Debates over the census are usually reserved for demographers and statisticians, but the dispute over the citizenship question is one of high politics.
Seats in the House of Representatives and in state legislatures are allocated based on census data.
So far, the dispute over the citizenship question has followed a similar path.
They hope to reassure those who are not citizens that census data is kept confidential by law.
Census experts predicted that 6.5 million or more people will go uncounted if the citizenship question is added.